<p>Semax is one of the most extensively studied nootropic peptides in the world, yet most people outside of Russia have never heard of it. Developed at Moscow's Institute of Molecular Genetics in the 1980s, it's been a registered pharmaceutical there since the early 2000s &mdash; prescribed for stroke recovery, cognitive disorders, and optic nerve conditions.</p>

<p>The peptide is a synthetic fragment of adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), specifically the 4&ndash;7 amino acid sequence with an added proline-glycine-proline tail for enzymatic stability. Unlike its parent hormone, Semax doesn't affect cortisol or adrenal function. Its effects are concentrated entirely on the brain &mdash; enhancing neurotrophic factor expression, modulating neurotransmitter activity, and improving cerebral blood flow.</p>

<div class="d">
