<tr><td><strong>Mood and stress</strong></td><td>Serotonin/dopamine modulation, enkephalinase inhibition</td><td class="y">Moderate &mdash; clinical observations + user data</td><td>Reduced anxiety, improved emotional resilience, less procrastination</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Motivation and drive</strong></td><td>Dopaminergic pathway modulation</td><td class="y">Moderate &mdash; mechanistic + anecdotal</td><td>Increased initiative, tasks feel less effortful</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Immune modulation</strong></td><td>Cytokine and immune pathway influence</td><td class="y">Low-Moderate &mdash; early research</td><td>Less frequently reported by nootropic users</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Visual function</strong></td><td>NGF-mediated optic nerve support</td><td class="y">Low-Moderate &mdash; Russian clinical studies</td><td>Niche application; primarily studied in optic nerve conditions</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<div class="d">
  <div class="s">An Important Distinction</div>
  <p>Semax isn't a stimulant. It doesn't produce the jitteriness, crash, or tolerance escalation associated with caffeine, amphetamines, or modafinil. The cognitive effects come from <strong>structural improvements in brain function</strong> &mdash; more BDNF, more synaptic connections, better neurotransmitter balance &mdash; rather than simply masking fatigue. This means the benefits tend to build over a cycle rather than spike and fade within hours.</p>
</div>

<!-- ========== VARIANTS ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Semax Variants: Standard vs. N-Acetyl vs. NASA</h2>

<p>Three variants exist, each with different potency and stability profiles. The chemical modifications affect how quickly the peptide is broken down by enzymes, which determines how long it remains active in the body.</p>

<div class="g3">
  <div class="mc">
    <h4 style="color:var(--blue);">Standard Semax</h4>
    <p><strong>Modification:</strong> Unmodified heptapeptide. <strong>Potency:</strong> 1x (baseline). <strong>Duration:</strong> Shortest. <strong>Research:</strong> Most extensively studied in Russian clinical trials. <strong>Best for:</strong> General cognitive support, beginners, those who want the most evidence-backed form.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="mc">
    <h4 style="color:var(--plum);">N-Acetyl Semax</h4>
    <p><strong>Modification:</strong> Acetyl group on N-terminus. <strong>Potency:</strong> 1.5&ndash;2x standard. <strong>Duration:</strong> Moderate. <strong>Research:</strong> Limited direct studies. <strong>Best for:</strong> Users seeking enhanced effects with longer duration than standard form.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="mc">
    <h4 style="color:var(--amber);">NASA Semax (N-Acetyl Semax Amidate)</h4>
    <p><strong>Modification:</strong> Acetyl + C-terminus amidation. <strong>Potency:</strong> 2&ndash;4x standard. <strong>Duration:</strong> Longest. <strong>Research:</strong> Least clinical data; popular in nootropic community. <strong>Best for:</strong> Experienced users seeking maximum potency for demanding cognitive tasks.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Standard Semax</th><th>N-Acetyl Semax</th><th>NASA Semax</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>Enzymatic stability</strong></td><td class="y">Moderate</td><td class="g">Improved</td><td class="g">Highest</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Bioavailability</strong></td><td class="y">Good (shorter half-life)</td><td class="g">Better</td><td class="g">Best</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Clinical evidence</strong></td><td class="g">Extensive (Russian trials)</td><td class="y">Limited</td><td class="r">Minimal</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Typical nasal dose</strong></td><td>300&ndash;600 mcg/day</td><td>600&ndash;1200 mcg/day</td><td>1.5&ndash;3 mg/day</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<div class="d-a">
  <div class="s">Choosing a Variant</div>
  <p>If you're new to Semax, <strong>start with the standard form</strong>. It has the deepest evidence base and is the version used in all Russian pharmaceutical studies. The modified variants are more potent per milligram, but potency without clinical data is a trade-off, not an upgrade. Graduate to N-Acetyl or NASA only after establishing your response to standard Semax.</p>
</div>

<!-- ========== DOSING ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Dosing Protocols</h2>

<div class="d-r">
  <div class="s">Important</div>
  <p>These are research-based protocols, not medical prescriptions. <strong>Always work with a qualified healthcare provider</strong> before starting any peptide regimen. Start with the lowest effective dose and increase gradually while monitoring your response.</p>
</div>

<h3>Intranasal Dosing (Preferred Route)</h3>

<p>The intranasal route is preferred because the nasal mucosa provides a relatively direct pathway to the brain, bypassing the blood-brain barrier. Split your daily dose between both nostrils. Tilt your head slightly forward when spraying &mdash; not backward &mdash; so the solution contacts the nasal lining rather than dripping down your throat.</p>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Variant</th><th>Daily Dose</th><th>Split Doses</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>Standard Semax</strong></td><td>300&ndash;600 mcg</td><td>150&ndash;300 mcg per nostril, 1&ndash;2x/day</td><td>Best starting point; most evidence</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>N-Acetyl Semax</strong></td><td>600&ndash;1200 mcg</td><td>300&ndash;600 mcg per nostril, 1&ndash;2x/day</td><td>For enhanced effects beyond standard</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>NASA Semax</strong></td><td>1.5&ndash;3 mg</td><td>750&ndash;1500 mcg per nostril, 1&ndash;2x/day</td><td>Most potent; start low</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h3>Subcutaneous Dosing</h3>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Variant</th><th>Daily Dose</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>Standard Semax</strong></td><td>500&ndash;1500 mcg</td><td>Once daily or split into two doses; systemic absorption</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>N-Acetyl / NASA</strong></td><td>Not commonly used SubQ</td><td>Intranasal preferred for these variants</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p><strong>Timing:</strong> Morning and early afternoon doses align with peak cognitive demands. Avoid evening dosing if sleep interference is a concern. Semax typically comes as lyophilized powder requiring reconstitution with bacteriostatic water. See our <a href="/articles/how-to-reconstitute-peptides">reconstitution guide</a> for instructions.</p>

<!-- ========== CLINICAL RESEARCH ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Clinical Research: What the Evidence Actually Shows</h2>

<p>Semax has been the subject of extensive research, primarily in Russia, where it holds pharmaceutical status. The clinical applications go well beyond general cognitive enhancement.</p>

<h3>Stroke Recovery</h3>

<div class="cd ct">
  <div class="tg">Clinical Evidence</div>
  <h3>Acute Ischemic Stroke</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:0;"><strong>Setting:</strong> Multiple controlled trials in Russian clinical settings &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Population:</strong> Acute ischemic stroke patients &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Route:</strong> Intranasal Semax alongside standard stroke care &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Key Findings:</strong> Reduced infarct volume, faster neurological recovery, improved motor function, speech, and cognition compared to controls &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Mechanism:</strong> Combined neuroprotection via BDNF, improved cerebral blood flow, and anti-inflammatory action</p>
</div>

<p>Patients receiving intranasal Semax showed faster recovery of motor function, speech, and cognitive ability compared to control groups. The neuroprotective effects are attributed to its combined action on BDNF, blood flow, and inflammatory pathways (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9378658/">Gusev et al., 1997</a>).</p>

<h3>Cognitive Disorders</h3>

<p>Clinical studies have explored Semax in patients with cognitive impairment and early-stage dementia. Results indicate improvements in attention, working memory, and executive function. These benefits align with what healthy users report anecdotally, though the magnitude of effect tends to be more pronounced in cognitively impaired populations.</p>

<h3>Optic Nerve Conditions</h3>

<p>One of the more surprising research findings involves Semax's effects on visual function. Studies in patients with optic nerve atrophy showed improvements in visual acuity and visual field, likely driven by NGF-mediated support of optic nerve neurons (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11109528/">Polunin et al., 2000</a>).</p>

<div class="d-a">
  <div class="s">Research Limitation</div>
  <p>The majority of Semax research comes from Russian institutions and is published in Russian-language journals. Large-scale Western randomized controlled trials are lacking. The existing evidence is consistent and the mechanisms are well-understood, but the research base doesn't meet the same methodological standards that Western regulators require for drug approval. This is an important caveat when evaluating the strength of evidence.</p>
</div>

<!-- ========== SEMAX VS SELANK ========== -->
<hr class="sep">
<h2>Semax vs. Selank: The Classic Comparison</h2>

<p>These two Russian nootropic peptides are frequently discussed together, and for good reason. They complement each other well but serve fundamentally different primary purposes.</p>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Semax</th><th>Selank</th></tr></thead>
